## Per-finding readings

### Finding 1 — bulk-close broadcast race (sessions_bulk.py:333-340)

`_bulk_close()` finishes with `await db.commit()` at line 189. The
route then iterates `for r in results: if r.ok: row = await
sessions_db.get(db, r.session_id)` at lines 336-338 and only publishes
the upsert when `row is not None`. Between the commit at 189 and the
re-fetch at 338, a concurrent `DELETE FROM sessions` (e.g. another bulk
op or the per-row delete endpoint) can remove the row, which silently
suppresses the broadcast. The other open tabs then never see the close,
so their sidebar shows the session as still open.

The audit fix hint — "capture rows inside the tx before commit, or use
data returned by `_bulk_close()` directly" — is testable: change
`_bulk_close()` to return the (id, closed_at, updated_at) tuple per ok
result, then build `_to_out`-equivalent payloads from a single
in-transaction SELECT before commit. Verdict: STILL_OPEN.

### Finding 2 — tag cardinality not enforced at PATCH (sessions.py)

`_validate_tag_cardinality()` (lines 161-212) is invoked in
`create_session` at line 371. The PATCH handler `patch_session` at
lines 435-516 accepts a `tag_ids` field, validates id existence
(lines 456-473), and writes via `tags_db.set_for_session` at line 510.
It NEVER calls `_validate_tag_cardinality`. Audit #5 (tags & sidebar)
flagged the same gap, raising independent confidence. Fix: insert
`await _validate_tag_cardinality(db, new_tag_ids)` after the existence
check completes and before `update_fields` runs, so PATCH rejects
two-project / two-severity sets with 422. Verdict: STILL_OPEN.

(Note: the docstring of `_validate_tag_cardinality` lines 165-176
explicitly carves out the *single-attach* path
`PUT /api/sessions/{sid}/tags/{tid}` as intentionally exempt. PATCH is
a bulk-replace path — `set_for_session` replaces the tag set
wholesale — so the carve-out does not apply. The audit's framing is
correct.)

### Finding 3 — bulk-export null filtering missing in frontend

`bulkExportSessions` at `sessionsBulk.ts:148-151` returns
`resp.blob()` raw, with no decode → filter → re-serialize step. The
caller `handleMultiExport` in `SessionList.svelte:456-466` URL-creates
the raw blob and drives a download. The behavior doc (lines 305-313)
says the response shape is `{"sessions": [SessionExport|null, ...]}`
and "the frontend filters them out before triggering the download" —
nothing fulfils that contract today. A user who selects a session-id
that the server doesn't find will get a download whose JSON contains
`null` slots, which the import path will not silently survive.

Two acceptable fixes: (a) JSON-parse the response, filter `null` from
`sessions[]`, re-serialize and blob; (b) move the filter server-side
and update `docs/behavior/sessions.md` accordingly. Verdict: STILL_OPEN.

### Finding 4 — checklist sessions can be closed (sessions.py:537-551)

`close_session` handler at lines 537-551 reads `sessions_db.close(db,
session_id)` and returns the row. It does not check `row.kind` against
`KNOWN_SESSION_KINDS`. A `kind="checklist"` session can be POSTed to
`/close` and the row's `closed_at` will be set, despite checklist
sessions not being prompt-runnable. The prompt endpoint (per
`prompt-endpoint.md` §"Failure responses" line 82) returns 409 on
closed sessions, so the inconsistent state never leaks user-visible
behavior — but it is a reachable bad state. Fix: gate by kind, e.g.
`if row.kind not in CLOSEABLE_SESSION_KINDS: raise 422`. Verdict:
STILL_OPEN.

